**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**
bug

**What is the current behavior?**
If we happen to use `context` as value name to pass down the prop to child components then the value `context` is `undefined`. 

**Example Snippet:**
Example component with Context Provider,
```
import React from 'react';
import ExampleComponentTwo from './ExampleComponentTwo';
import ExampleContext from './ExampleContext';

class ExampleComponentOne extends React.Component {
    constructor(props){
        super(props);
    }

    render(){
        return(
            <div>
                <h2> I'm Example ONE</h2>
                <ExampleContext.Provider context="BOB">
                    <ExampleComponentTwo />
                </ExampleContext.Provider>
            </div>
        )
    }
}

export default ExampleComponentOne;
```
Example component with Context Consumer,
```
import React from 'react';
import ExampleContext from './ExampleContext';

class ExampleComponentTwo extends React.Component {
    constructor(props){
        super(props);
    }

    render(){
        return(
            <div>
                <h2> I'm Example TWO </h2>
                <ExampleContext.Consumer>
                    {(context) => { console.log(" Name: "+context)}}
                </ExampleContext.Consumer>
            </div>
        )
    }
}

export default ExampleComponentTwo;
```
Context Component,
```
import React from 'react';
const ExampleContext = React.createContext();
export default ExampleContext;
```
    
**What is the expected behavior?**
Unless `context` is a keyword it should behave as any other prop name. ( example: `value` as defined in react docs for Context api example )

     
